TY  - JOUR
AU  - Segal, Ilya
T1  - Collusion, Exclusion, and Inclusion in Random-Order Bargaining
PY  - 2003
Y1  - 2003/04/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00251
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 70
IS  - 2
SP  - 439
EP  - 460
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper examines the profitability of three types of integration in a cooperative game solved by a random-order value (e.g. the Shapley value). Collusion between players i and j is a contract merging their resources in the hands of one of them, say i. This contract can be represented as a combination of exclusion, which lets i exclude j's resource but not use it himself, and inclusion, which lets i use j's resource but not exclude j from it. This representation yields a third-difference condition on the characteristic function that determines the profitability of collusion, generalizing existing results for specific games. Namely, collusion is profitable [unprofitable] when the complementarity of the colluding players is reduced [increased] by other players.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00251
ER  - 



